I just saw the film. SPOILERS:

The film is horrible. Sure, it takes a darker route and follows the original tales more faithfully (like having Cinderella's sisters chop off their legs so they may fit in the shoe) but the ending was just plain horrible. It basically closes with a relatively happy ending for a bunch of murderers. Jack is the one who steals both 5 golden coins and a golden egg from the giants in the sky, and the giants let him get away with it, and then he goes back up and also steals the golden harp, then the giant decides to act so Jack practically murders him. And not only that, then the giant's wife also gets down to Earth to claim justice for her husband's death and she gets murdered by Jack as well, with the assistance of Red Riding Hood and Cinderella. What the fuck was this horseshit?

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment: I just reached an epiphany on the philosophy of the movie: The importance of going out, taking risks, and learning from your mistakes/experiences. Even though Red got eaten, and had to be saved, she appreciated her experiences, deviating from the path, and then started walking with a knife. Rapunzel snuck around, and learned that she could love someone more than she did her "mother", and that the way her mother showed her love, wasn't healthy. The boy was supposed to simply sell the cow for money, but he instead bought a magic bean story, that turned out to be true, and gave him enjoyment, for a while, before everything went to shit. The witch was in strict pursuit of good looks, but even after she got them, learning that she'd just lost her daughter's love, due to neglecting her happiness for all those years, was enough to make her go mad. Cinderella discovered love, but also betrayal, strength, and independence. The Baker's wife goes and acknowledges that she may desire someone other than her husband. The Baker's misadventures lead him to forgiving in his father, and forming an instant family.

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment:
Shame on you Disney....

First, let me address fans of the Musical "Into the Woods." ¬†I have no doubt that the musical itself is very enjoyable. ¬†The dark themes and existential question it confronts are great and things I typically relish. ¬†The common retort, I hear, is, "what did you expect?...it's a 'dark' musical "not meant for kids!" ¬†

Agreed! ¬†But mind you, not everybody has had the cultural privileges of being acquainted with every musical, and this is no small group. ¬†To this majority demographic, one must rely on the traditional avenues for judgement on the content of a film: 1) Trailer ¬†2) Rating 3) The studio making the film.

In this case, we have a trailer that does not expose the adult nature of the film; we have rating of PG, and under the banner of Disney. ¬†Furthermore, every preview of the film was targeted at children.

*spoiler alert*

So what about the film was so egregious in its inappropriateness to children? ¬†How about the themes of sexual lust? ¬†(Prince Charming seduces one of the main protagonists' wife, and she willingly obliged) Pedophilia? ¬†(Johnny Depps 'Fox' character has "White Van no windows" undertones) Meaningless death? (many are killed for no apparent reason other than to say the world is cruel.) ¬†Mind you, I am no prude, I can critically sit through ¬†Gaspar No√© Irreversible and not even flinch. ¬†But I would like to keep my children's innocence for at least some of their childhood, thank you very much, Disney.

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment:
I saw the movie today and I have quite mixed views on it. (Spoiler alert) 

It was good film with a great cast however I felt quite a few scenes were unnecessary. Such as the prince seducing the baker's wife, the baker's wife dying etc and after the wedding scene it felt like the film just went downhill after that and that it should have ended then. I understand it was to show a tragic ending but it just felt slightly unnecessary. Some of the scenes were not scary but not suitable for PG such as the mother cutting her daughter's feet, the birds blinding them etc. there were so many different plots that none of them were detailed. Found it enjoyable but a bit confused with all the different plots.

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment:
I have watched Annie, Wicked, Legally Blonde, Phantom of the Opera, Hairspray, Les Moserable and so many more musicals, and I have never seen a musical that I was thoroughly disappointed at and completely disliked until I went to watch "Into the Woods." All of the songs did not leave me humming. I did not find any of the songs catchy or clever. The plot was horrendous. Everything about the plot was random and irrelevant. The plot was not well written. The tragic part at the end of the movie was random and irrelevant to the whole story. The movie would have been a lot better if they didn't add the tragic part (not that it would be good, just better).There was no central moral or any enlightening and special moments. The characters were bland and lacked charisma as well as uniqueness. The baker's singing skill was not up to par. [SPOILER] The death of some of the characters were irrelevant and not very well written.

I absolutely hate this musical. I feel like I have wasted 2 hours and 4 minutes watching it. I want my money back! Please do not go watch it!

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment:
my exp. with musicals is the Peter Pan one starring Mary Martin (which¬†i watched obsessively on VHS as a kid)¬†& the Psych musical episode (which¬†i liked). so while i don't consider myself a musical fan, i guess it's no surprise i enjoyed this one. beware, people who tune out music after a while. ITW requires close listening, for the songs/lyrics make up the dialogue and are interconnected.

i was surprised by how funny it is. laughed out loud a lot; sometimes i was the only one. there was constant laughing near my area, where most of the adults sat (range of 20s to middle age), and silence in front‚Äîkid zone‚Äîfor those same scenes. that should give an idea of how one's understanding plays a part in enjoying ITW.

the plot ties together Jack and the Beanstalk, Cinderella, Little Red Riding Hood, and Rapunzel in an interesting way. while those are well-known as fairy tales, i like how ITW presents them¬†in the form of¬†a fable. tip: searching for/questioning¬†that lesson while watching might hold your attention in the movie more.

for a character not emphasized early on, the Baker became¬†my favorite. by the end he's the binding force in the other characters' lives, in an ironic Happily Ever After. i'd have liked his connection to Rapunzel, which¬†viewers learn early on, revealed.¬†in fact, Rapunzel basically disappears near the end so her storyline isn't concluded at all. minor gripes though.

Comment: Just saw this movie a couple hours ago. Here is my opinion: Everyone in this movie should win Oscars for singing and acting and all in all making this film one of the only good musical-movies, especially Meryl Streep. This is one of her greatest achievements, singing and acting-wise. And Emily Blunt too. Overall, the message of this movie is clear and true: Be careful what you wish for, because sometimes if you want something bad enough, you will do anything to get it, telling yourself that the end justifies the means, without giving one thought to the repercussions. Lilla Crawford was her usual sterling self, just as mind-blowing as she was in Annie, maybe even more.James Corden was pretty good. I LOVED the scene where Chris Pine and Billy Magnussen performed "Agony", where, instead of making it sad and depressing, they made it overly dramatic hilariously. Chris has got an impressive set of pipes. Anna Kendrick was VERY good at singing Cinderella, but she didn't really play the part of the damsel in distress. Nothing wrong with that, though. Johnny Depp was awesome. MacKenzie Mauzy was okay. She didn't act and/or sing that well, but maybe that's just because she was surrounded by people who were AMAZING.¬†Daniel Huttlestone was good. Sang quite well, and not bad at acting. So all in all, I'd give this movie a 5 out of 5.

Title: Into The Woods Trailer - Now Playing In Theaters!
Comment: If you were someone that went into this movie not knowing it was based on a musical or did not know what happens in the musical then I understand completely if you don't like it. The advertising for this movie is deceiving. While I understand they do not want to give away that it is dark, it does mislead the audience so people who are just common movie goers could be disappointed. I will say ACT II of the "Into the Woods" musical is the true heart of it, but the movie in my opinion failed in this aspect. I won't spoil anything, but the movie bogged down and a lot of the scenes that brought the four main leads together felt forced. The characters swing moods to quickly and things happen abruptly. I still enjoyed the movie overall, but ACT II could have been done better. It's funny because finishing the movie at the end of ACT I, would have made a better movie for movie goers, but a poor adaption for the fans of the musical.

This now looks like a fantasy movie made back in the days where the cast were British of American accented white people.  Don't get me wrong the movie looks great,  but tell me how a black witch,  or a charming Asian prince of just random coloured people wouldn't make it just that much better,  involving the whole world into this fantasy picture rather than just pleasing the imagination of the Western white world?  One of the greatest things of Harry Potter was that the cast was so diverse and I as a small kid always wanted to go to Hogwarts too because hey,  I saw every possible race in there,  it was somewhere I could have gone too. Even though the protagonists where white that doesn't matter because it's how Rowling invisioned it, we're not claiming to always put in random coloured people in major roles for racial diversity but why leave them out if there are indeed roles they could have portrayed.  Plus it would offer more roles for coloured actors to pursue because it's still an issue that coloured actors have a way harder time of being casted into various roles.. Comment: So the cast isn't ethnically diverse. These fairytails' heritages stem from countries with a mostly white population. Why? Because it's accurate. So why are dragons and magic in the movie? Because it is accurate to the story. A lot would say that it is racist to take a beloved story focused mainly on black people and cast white people to portray them. Vice versa? Totally fine. Double standard, much? What I'm trying to get at as that we should be more concerned with the core plot of the movie, not the skin color of the people portraying them. I would understand the moaning and groaning if this film outright made someone who was clearly another ethnicity than Caucasian white, but that isn't the case. Just enjoy the movie or don't see it at all. All this bitching isn't necessary, you guys.¬†

Comment:
I will never understand the people who cry and bitch at the lack of diversity in movies. There are also the people who cry and bitch when movies change things (as in the race of a character). I mean, all of the Brothers Grimm fairy tales are set in Germany, which consisted of mainly white people. I understand if it's a random movie that has only white characters, but the origins of these fairy tales make it necessary to have a white cast.
People who demand a diverse cast mess up things too. An example would be the upcoming Fantastic Four movie. The origins of the Fantastic Four are an all white cast. So, what do we do? We make the Human Torch black! But wait a minute... the Human Torch and Invisible Woman are siblings. "Oh no problem. It's possible. He could be adopted." Unnecessary changes are upsetting.

Comment: I love, love, love Into The Woods, and I was so excited when I heard a movie was coming out, but I was also a bit hesitant to actually watch the trailer until now, for fear that I might absolutely hate it, and they might ruin one of my favorite musicals. I hadn't realized that this was going to be a Disney film, and although I am one of the biggest Disney fans you'll ever meet, I'm worried that, because it's Disney, (and PG,) it won't include the darker themes and humor. I imagine that they would have to alter the storylines and cut out quite a bit in order for it to be given a PG rating. I'm hoping for the best here, and it's great that kids are being introduced to it, but that will likely result in a watered-down, kid-friendly version.
